(Import [(31nz ([(Technology (Software (Programming Compilation)))] Decision [|Schema supports inline declaration and file-path references (paths resolved into the full spec before macro processing). A lowering executor recursively walks the NOTA schema tree dispatching per node by bracket/paren shape, lowering transient sugar into canonical form: bare identifier = reference to a namespace entry (resolved by lookup); square-bracket vector = enum declaration with variants; single-paren single-identifier = newtype tuple wrapping the named type; multi-element parens = struct with positional fields; (fieldname [variants]) = inline named enum field. Schema node values lower by context; bare identifiers resolve to namespace objects.|] Medium Minimum Zero [schema nota lowering namespace])) (62r4 ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Modularity)))] Decision [The schema-derived stack uses separate repositories for nota-next, schema-next, and schema-rust-next rather than one combined integration repository.] Medium Minimum Zero [nota-next schema-next schema-rust-next])) (d3r2 ([(Technology (Software (Programming Compilation))) (Technology (Software (Programming Macros)))] Decision [|Component code-generation direction (designed/prototyped, not integrated): the schema generates a component's Rust by EXPANDING bound universal frames into concrete owned interfaces, not persisting generic aliases. Goal is narrow — generate repeated interface boilerplate: Input/Output and work/action enums, payload structs/newtypes/enums, standard inherent/trait impls (constructors, accessors, From legs, scalar-newtype Display/AsRef/comparisons), role/marker trait impls, an opt-in mechanical Deref the newtype shape proves, and later a VariantMatch for enum-rewrap. Traits/impls are the pipe-brace construct expressing Rust relationships as data so hand-written engine code accepts generated nouns through typed bounds. Method bodies are data ONLY for the small mechanical family the schema shape uniquely proves (newtype Deref projection); genuine business logic stays hand-written. The durable principle: a schema-authored body is valid only when every call resolves from the receiver's schema shape. Open pieces: generic impl-header emission with parameter-bound vocabulary, fn/signature sub-construct for trait declarations, ownership-aware payload-vs-into_payload projection, total VariantMatch. Settled constraints and the open how live in the schema-next and nota-next architecture files.|] Low Minimum Zero [schema-next nota-next schema-rust-next triad-runtime code-generation])) (el7z ([(Work Productivity)] Correction [|Keep working productively without stalling: do not block synchronously waiting for a dispatched subagent — run other work (own thinking, tool calls, context reading, chat prep) while it is in flight and check the result at a natural integration point, with multiple tools in flight. Mid-task info the psyche injects (a report, clarification, context — often via escape) is NOT an instruction to stop; absorb it and keep executing; only an explicit stop is an interruption. Treat transient connection warnings as non-blocking when tooling still works and resume the assigned job rather than detouring into debugging. Beads are coordination aids, not a substitute for implementation — work the bead/code path immediately unless blocked. In active troubleshooting where the user asked for a working result, apply a narrow safe fix rather than stopping at diagnosis. After subagent prototype work, run context maintenance and a fresh-intent audit over recent reports/code, then synthesize and implement sensible immediate fixes rather than letting stale context drive the next slice.|] High VeryHigh Zero [subagent work-continuity beads troubleshooting])) (q9n2 ([(Work Productivity)] Correction [Match effort to the request and stay within the asked scope: when the psyche asks whether something is possible or to research tools, deliver the research and assessment then stop — implementation requires explicit instruction. Size effort to the ask: a simple review or what-do-you-think wants a lightweight read-and-judge pass or single agent, reserving expensive adversarial fan-out for explicit thoroughness requests or work too large for one context. When work surfaces many open psyche questions, lean on pattern-recognition of captured intent and propose an MVP matching the letter of intent, surfacing only the truly-unanswerable remainder rather than dozens of inferable questions.] High High Zero [scope research mvp effort-sizing])) (0xqp ([(Work Productivity)] Principle [Running a Spirit Observe is standard routine practice, not optional: agents observe recent Spirit records as a matter of course — proactively at the start of and during substantive work — to let recorded intent guide the work, not only when the Spirit gate flags intent as unclear; just do it as a guide rather than presenting it to the psyche as an open decision.] High Minimum Zero [spirit observe intent])) (pb1g ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Modularity))) (Technology (Software (Security Authorization)))] Clarification [|Every component needs a meta slot because configuration must not be reachable through the ordinary working-signal surface; if no separate meta-signal repo exists, the component repo itself creates and carries the meta-signal surface. A contract is split into separate signal-component and meta-signal-component repos for three reasons: rebuild-churn isolation (peers depend on the small contract repo and recompile only on wire-contract changes, not internal edits), security-sensitivity visibility (owner-only ops live in a distinct meta repo, making sensitive edits obvious and letting non-owner clients avoid depending on it), and meta-signal being optional (components with no owner relationship need only the ordinary signal contract). The split is about compilation/dependency isolation and authority clarity, not where state or logic lives.|] High Medium Zero [meta-signal signal-component contract-repo component-triad])) (q33b ([(Technology (Software (Security Authorization)))] Principle [|Owner/permission/unpermission distinction can live as a data-type Permission variant (Owner/Permission/Unpermission) inside the signal, with a general socket routing by variant prefix. Current implementation keeps the two-socket filesystem-managed approach (ordinary socket + owner socket, access controlled by filesystem) — that stays; the macro implements as-if-two-sockets so a message is authenticated by the socket it arrived on. Permission-in-signal-variant is deferred until needed; development mode runs as local user trusting itself.|] High Minimum Zero [signal owner-socket permission authorization])) (vudl ([(Technology (Software (Security Authorization)))] Decision [|lojix uses the two-contract authority split: Deploy/Pin/Unpin/Retire are owner-only policy in meta-signal-lojix (a deploy mutates the live cluster and can break the router, the strongest owner-socket case); Query, the WatchDeployments/WatchCacheRetention subscriptions, and Unwatch are peer-callable in the ordinary signal-lojix. The policy contract is born meta-signal-lojix, never owner-signal-lojix. Until cutover carry meta-signal-lojix as a local path-dependency package inside the lojix tree (mirroring the cloud stopgap); create the standalone repo at cutover.|] High Minimum Zero [lojix meta-signal-lojix signal-lojix authority-split])) (2foy ([(Technology (Software (Security Authorization)))] Constraint [|A content/data daemon's privilege boundary is can-ingest-and-serve-content, not can-read-anything-on-the-system: it is fairly privileged (ingesting/serving content is not especially dangerous) but never absolutely privileged. Its store stays unwritable by anything except the daemon itself — even root writing it is system misbehavior. It has no ambient access to system private-key material and, handed a path to a private key, must be unable to read it.|] Medium Medium Zero [content-daemon privilege-boundary access-control])) (a4i6 ([(Technology (Software (Security Authorization))) (Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture)))] Decision [|Each agent has its own Criome identity, created at agent start, recorded in persona-mind; the agent's Criome public key is the authoritative authentication anchor. Complex (especially agent-initiated) Criome interactions run through the agent's own Criome daemon, and authorization is checked against Criome rather than SSH for many workspace operations — every component/daemon can escalate to Criome for an authorization check. The substrate is per-component-per-domain agent spaces. criome is per-Unix-user: each user runs their own home criome daemon with their own key custody, the Unix-user boundary being the trust boundary; there is no single shared multi-user system daemon (that would collapse every user behind one compromise point). The privileged system criome tier is for host-scoped system services under a service user that a home criome peers with, not a shared daemon — the same single-Unix-user custody boundary that rules out an embeddable criome engine library.|] Medium Medium Zero [criome agent-identity persona-mind unix-user authorization])) (qmsh ([(Technology (Software (Security Authorization)))] Constraint [Firmware gating reuses existing policy surfaces rather than adding broad Horizon schema.] Low Minimum Zero [firmware horizon access-control])) (f8m3 ([(Technology (Software (Programming Parsing)))] Decision [|NOTA has two bracket-string forms: [content] inline-bracket-string for single-line strings; [|content\\|] block-string for multi-line strings and for strings safely containing single [ or ] without escaping (delimited [| / \\|] so content may include [, ], or newlines freely). Both are distinct NOTA shapes the shape-logic layer distinguishes via is_block_string and the underlying parser.|] High Minimum Zero [nota bracket-string block-string parser])) (kfqa ([(Technology (Software (Programming Parsing)))] Decision [|The schema reader is multi-pass NOTA-first: one universal NOTA parser produces a generic NotaValue tree, then context-sensitive macro passes interpret values per their NodeDefinitionPoint position, then assembly produces canonical schema — one syntax (NOTA), one parser, multiple semantic passes. NOTA parsing breaks down by object via positional ranges: each block tracks its source span and carries shape predicates (is_square_bracket_block / is_parenthesis_block / is_brace_block; holds_single/two/N_root_objects; recursive predicates like second_root_object_is_a_square_bracket_object), and each root object inside a block is itself a typed/positioned block, so the recursive parsing chain IS the chain of block-level queries. Schema parsing first identifies NOTA delimiters and their roles (parens for enum/variant, square brackets for vector-like sequences and string-derived token vectors, curly braces for name-value namespace maps), then runs passes per source block: pass 1 finds identifier uses and locations, pass 2 registers inline declarations into the namespace and resolves references by lookup — supporting bare-PascalCase-or-explicit-Variant-Payload shorthand, with the source representation (not lowered fields) telling whether each identifier defines, references, or both. NotaBodyDecode is the semantic decode entry point: document/block decode strip their wrapper context and delegate to the body decoder. After structural parsing matches a file body or delimited object, the next semantic step receives the matched body's inner object stream rather than the outer delimiter wrapper, and the expected type decides whether the body reads as struct, vector, enum variant, or other value. Schema source needs its own typed node model before assembled schema — a streamlined tree of typed structural-macro nodes, namespaces, paths, fields, variants, references representing syntax directly (including inline PascalCase local declarations and self-named field shorthand) — and schema can act as its own codec so shorthand round-trips as typed data rather than being a one-way parser convenience. Block reassembly concatenates blocks one-after-another; parsed blocks are first-class units re-emitted in order without nesting reconstruction.|] High Minimum Zero [schema nota parser nota-body-decode namespace])) (t4gd ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Modularity)))] Principle [A daemon binary compiles with no NOTA code at all: NOTA encode/decode is a thin-CLI text-edge concern only, the daemon speaks binary/rkyv exclusively and must not pull nota-next into its artifact. Component crates gate NOTA behind a nota-text feature only the CLI binary enables, so the daemon build is NOTA-free, pairing with signal being NOTA-free.] VeryHigh Minimum Zero [daemon nota rkyv nota-next signal])) (rc8v ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Modularity)))] Decision [|Drop the persona- prefix from component crate names workspace-wide: spirit/router/message/mind/orchestrate/harness/terminal/introspect/system/engine-management rename persona-X → X (and signal-persona-X → signal-X, owner-signal-persona-X → owner-signal-X). Exceptions keeping persona-: agent-harness components (persona-codex, persona-claude, persona-pi, persona-gemini, persona-open-code) since they are agent-process harnesses, not architectural-pattern components. Persona itself stays persona — that is its name, not a prefix.|] High High Zero [persona crate-naming spirit signal])) (f8ds ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Modularity)))] Decision [|Component triad pipeline split: Signal interface declaration lives in the signal-<component> contract repo (clients depend on it; the daemon imports all Signal types from it — the contract repo is canonical for client-facing Signal types), while Nexus and SEMA interface declarations live in the daemon repo as daemon-internal runtime concerns; when a daemon grows a separate scale-out database the SEMA interface may